BASH commands

pwd | print work directory. / |  denotes root at the beginning.

ls |  list of files

mkdir |  make directory

~ | navigate to home directory

rmdir | remove directory

FLAGS | True or False. Add a flag to a command to change its behaviour.
- one hyphen on UNIX. -- two hyphens on LINUX
eg. ls -author

HIDDEN files | Hidden files start with a period, eg. .hidden
View hidden files by adding the flag -a, which stands for all
eg. ls -a

CREATE new file | touch = creates a new file
eg. use it to create a hidden file. touch .self_taught
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

PIPES

The pipe in UNIX is (|) The vertical bar is a pipe.
You can use a pipe to pass the output of a command to another command
as its input.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ENVIRONMENTAL VARIABLES

are stored in your operating system, that programs can use to get data
about the environment they are running in such as the name of computer...
You can create a new environmental variable in BASH with syntax
export variable_name = [variable_value]

eg. export x = 100
echo $x
>> 100

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

MANUAL pages

man <command> | Look up the manual page for a particular command.
man -k <search term>
    Do a keyowrd search for all manual pages containing the given search term.
/<term> | Within a manual page, perform a search for 'term'

n | After performing a search within a manual page, select the next found item.

q | Quit man pages

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

cp | Copy - ie. Copy a file or directory

mv | Move - ie. Move a file or directory (can also be used to rename).

rm | Remove - ie. Delete a file.

No Undo (be careful when performing destructive actions).

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GIT commnads

The most commonly used git commands are:
   add        Add file contents to the index
   bisect     Find by binary search the change that introduced a bug
   branch     List, create, or delete branches
   checkout   Checkout a branch or paths to the working tree
   clone      Clone a repository into a new directory
   commit     Record changes to the repository
   diff       Show changes between commits, commit and working tree, etc
   fetch      Download objects and refs from another repository
   grep       Print lines matching a pattern
   init       Create an empty Git repository or reinitialize an existing one
   log        Show commit logs
   merge      Join two or more development histories together
   mv         Move or rename a file, a directory, or a symlink
   pull       Fetch from and integrate with another repository or a local branch
   push       Update remote refs along with associated objects
   rebase     Forward-port local commits to the updated upstream head
   reset      Reset current HEAD to the specified state
   rm         Remove files from the working tree and from the index
   show       Show various types of objects
   status     Show the working tree status
   tag        Create, list, delete or verify a tag object signed with GPG


